data.description:
Create a password hashing function that turns any 1-20 character string into a hash.

You are free to design any hashing function you please as long as you follow the guidelines:

1) Hashes should be always 8 characters long.

2) Hashes shouldn't resemble the input:

```javascript
// returns 's3cr3tAA' which resembles the original too much!
var hashed = badHash('secret');

// returns 'XMDERT21' which doesn't resemble the original, except for length
var hashed = betterHash('secret');
```

3) Hashing the same input should result in the same result:
```javascript
// results in 'af12FKla'
var hashed = badHash('secret');

// the next call result is 'af12FKl1'
var hashed = badHash('secret');

// this should return true:
betterHash('secret') == betterHah('secret')

```

4) Hashes of two slightly differing passwords shouldn't look similar:

```javascript
// returns 'abcf12le'
var hash1 = badHash('secret_1');

// returns 'abcf12li'
var hash2 = badHash('secret_2');

// returns 'abcf12le'
var hash3 = goodHash('secret_1');

// returns 'cdaf2fAG'
var hash4 = goodHash('secret_2');


```

During the final test, there should be less than 3 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collision_(computer_science)">collisions</a> among the 25,000 generated hashes:

```javascript
// results in 'cd12mal0'
var hashed1 = badHash('word1');

// also results in 'cd12mal0' which is a collision
var hashed2 = badHash('word2');
```

Your hashing function will be tested for collisions on a randomly generated array of 25,000 strings. Your algorithm is allowed to create at most 3 collisions. Anything above that will make the tests fail.


Note: In real life, implementing your own password hashing functions is not a good idea. Always rely on the work of people who are skilled in cryptography - your unique solution here is likely to have multiple vulnerabilities which would make it unsafe to use in real products. Treat this kata just as a fun exercise.
